dc:description: The KCNE1 gene has been associated with autosomal recessive Jervell and Lange-Nielsen Syndrome (JLNS) in 4 probands in 11 publications. At least 4 unique variants (missense, in-frame indel) have been reported in humans, and variants in this gene segregated with disease in 4 additional family members. KCNE1 was first associated with this disease in humans in 1997 (Tyson et al.). The mechanism for disease is homozygous loss of function causes irregular myocyte polarization from K+ channel activity leading to LQT and inner ear malformations causing HL and vestibular dysfunction (PMID: 9354783). This gene-disease association is supported by animal models, expression studies and in vitro functional assays showing the potential of variation in the protein to cause irregular heart conductivity and hearing loss. It is important to note that the KCNQ1 gene comprises a large percentage of the JLNS cases currently published in the literature and that though this appears to be a largely accepted gene-disease association, there is not quite enough case level information to reach a Definitive classification. However there is a large amount of experimental evidence showing the interaction between KCNE1 and KCNQ1 though this information was not scored. In summary, there is moderate evidence to support this gene-disease relationship. While more evidence is needed to establish this relationship definitively, no convincing contradictory evidence has emerged.
curationReasonDescription:
The LMM also has an additional homozygous internal case of the p.Tyr46Cys variant which segregated in a sibling with disease leading to the variant to be called LP (+ 0.5pt).

There is an article in French Denjoy et al. 2007 PMID: 17646758 that does not have PDF access and appears to have JLNS KCNE1 cases (186 total JLNS patients studied).

evidence.dc:description: mouse did not have long QT

This paper did not find an actual change in activation/ repolarization time. This could potentially be considered contradictory evidence, but there are several other knockout mouse studies that recapitulate the heart phenotype. i.e. Drici et al. 1998 9670922 found that there was a prolonged QT interval in these knockout mice. Regardless, it is important to note that this mouse didn't have prolonged QT and not score it.
evidence.rdfs:label: KCNE1-KO mice Cardio phenotype

evidence.dc:description: Used ECG to measure the QT intervals of the mice and found that there was a prolonged qT in the knockout mice at slower heart rates, but a shortened QT at faster heart rates relative to controls at those heart rates in Adult mice
evidence.rdfs:label: IsK knockout JLNS model

evidence.dc:description: Molecular mechanism is not consistent with human variants.

The KCNE1pkr homozygous mutant has profound bilateral deafness consistent with the JLNS phenotype and the isk-null mouse previously generated by Friedmann et al. 1996/Vetter et al. 1996. They also have inner ear defects i.e. collapse of Reissner's membrane.
evidence.rdfs:label: Punk rocker Mouse KCNE1pkr

evidence.dc:description: Molecular mechanism of human variants is inconsistent with this model

They say that IsK knockout induced deafness may be a new class of deafness, and though they did not test for longQT in these mice, this is consistent with the JLNS hearing phenotype that is only seen in recessive inheritance
evidence.rdfs:label: IsK knockout mouse

evidence.dc:description: Found that there was a significant impact in KvLQT1 and HERG currents in HEK293 cells/oocytes.  Also measured deactivation time constants of minK+KvLQT1 and minK+HERG. They found that different mutations had different cellular phenotypes. They found that generally these missense mutations, i.e. D76N had strong dominant negative effects on KvLQT1 and suppressed the activity.
evidence.rdfs:label: minK variants in Xenopus oocytes and HEK293 cells

evidence.dc:description: The variants were tested in Xenopus laevis oocytes via cRNA injection. They tested the voltage dependence of the current constant as well as the deactivation time and found lower current in the cells injected with the variant hminK subunits. Though Bianchi et al. 1999 was also scored for functional alteration of the electrochemical properties of the KCNE1 protein, both were given points because they used different cell lines (oocytes vs. HEK293) and different variants. Both variants lowered deactivation time constants.
evidence.rdfs:label: D76N and S74L Affect Iks function

evidence.dc:description: Immunolocalization shown in the vestibule as well as the kidney. This study also has a mouse model suitable for the JLNS phenotype, but points were already maxed out for animal models.
evidence.rdfs:label: Expression of KCNE1 and KO Mouse

evidence.dc:description: This paper also conducted current studies and generated minK null mice however, they also noted that there was expression of minK in wild type neonatal mice. They did also find evidence to suggest that minK expression is an early event in conduction system development and that its restricted nature of expression suggests species-specific roles in mediating electrophysiological properties of the heart.
evidence.rdfs:label: Mouse Model with myocyte characterization

evidence.dc:description: The patient's mother was identified to be heterozygous along with her half sister, but the origin of the other allele is unknown. Functional evidence allows this to be scored, but not at the full 1pt.

evidence.phenotypeFreeText: JLNS with congenital profound deafness and LQTS
evidence.previousTestingDescription:
Patients with clinical diagnoses of LQTS and their family members
were referred from cardiology clinics in North America and represented
diverse ethnic backgrounds. Peripheral blood for DNA extraction
was collected after informed consent was obtained according to
guidelines approved by the Children’s Hospital Institutional Review
Board. Additional data collected included clinical and family histories
of syncope, palpitations, seizures, hearing loss/deficiency, and sudden
cardiac death, as well as surface ECGs, exercise tests (if available),
Holter studies (if available), and recent clinical notes from the referring
physicians. All probands met established criteria for LQTS.18 Ratecorrected
QT intervals were calculated by Bazett’s formula, where
QTc5QT/ ÖRR and have units of seconds1/2.19

evidence.dc:description: This variant was found in a consanguineous family in a homozygous state. The variant itself has not been found in gnomAD, however the Thr58Pro and Leu59Pro have both been found in 4/277122 and 4/277156 alleles in gnomAD respectively with no homozygotes. There only further evidence reported is that the mutation of the Thr59 residue to a valine was shown to reduce channel activity Takumi 1991. Valine is more structurally similar to Thr than Pro, so this may count as sufficient evidence to score the missense, though the consanguinity/homozygosity does not allow for the default 1 pt.

evidence.rdfs:label: UK1S II-1
evidence.detectionMethod:
A genome-wide search in family UK1S demonstrated a
region of homozygosity by descent on chromosome 21 with
D21S261 after 50 markers had been genotyped. The maximum lod scores for this small family at zero
recombination were 1.47 for D21S1252 and 1.69 for D21S1895.
A candidate gene, the potassium channel IsK (minK) mapping
to the homozygous region, was screened for mutations in family
UK1S using SSCP
evidence.phenotypeFreeText: congenital profound sensorineural hearing loss with absent vestibular function, syncope upon exertion, prolonged QT
